g.title: EleanorRank2Convo3 begins.
g.text: EleanorRank2Convo3 begins.

g.title: j154952189
g.text: Okay, we’ve known each other a little while now, and you’re from the future, and I think I can trust you to be honest with me about this, so I have to ask the most important question.

g.title: j2929237922
g.text: Are we alone? Or did we finally contact something else?

g.title: j1363199868
g.text: You mean alien life? Not yet, but maybe one day.

g.title: j4239920616
g.text: The Indifference is the closest we’ve come, unfortunately.

g.title: j1061894939
g.text: Yeah, we’re alone. Nothing but humans and human-created things.

g.title: j2352817892
g.text: Well, shit.

g.title: j264818447
g.text: What IS ‘the Indifference’? I’ve seen glimpses in your mind, but I can’t make sense of it. It makes me want to run and curl up somewhere far away with very thick walls.

g.title: j2989478517
g.text: The bleakest possible answer.

g.title: j3459560854
g.text: I was really hoping there’d be something out there we could talk to. Something with a truly outside perspective on our species.

g.title: j2055565282
g.text: We’re still not sure what it is. Or even what it WANTS. We don’t even know if it’s an ancient entity like the Red Veil think it is, or if Albrecht brought it into being somehow.

g.title: j1628028079
g.text: It's the thing that took Major Rusalka.

g.title: j833734166
g.text: I’m not sure why. Intelligence is intelligence, after all. It shouldn’t matter whether we discover it or create it.

g.title: j2574480774
g.text: Talk to and… other things, of course.

g.title: j3438689682
g.text: If I tell you it’s what was possessing Major Rusalka, does that help?

g.title: j4054898453
g.text: Oh.

g.title: j926467057
g.text: I think I just wanted reassurance that the Universe hadn’t put all its eggs in one basket. Because if humans are all there is, then the situation’s pretty screwed.

g.title: j241718961
g.text: Looking for a fellow tentacle monster to befriend?

g.title: j1088261981
g.text: Wait. Just what sort of interaction did you have in mind?

g.title: j4098586078
g.text: Oh no.

g.title: j4047533737
g.text: Ah, well.

g.title: j3670166273
g.text: +5 Chemistry

g.title: j2756684564
g.text: Some kind of communion, I suppose. Not necessarily anything physical. I just want to touch minds with something that not only isn’t human, it isn’t even terrestrial.

g.title: j882099267
g.text: Oh SHIT.

g.title: Chat ends.
g.text: Chat ends.

g.title: j1297259343
g.text: Excuse you. I am not a 'tentacle monster'. I am a monster who happens to have A TENTACLE. One. So far.

g.title: j467702689
g.text: I tried to touch minds with one of Lettie’s rats, once, just to see what would happen.

g.title: j2192622494
g.text: THAT THING? That’s the same as your ‘Indifference’?

g.title: j100693297
g.text: If all I wanted to do was converse with things with tentacles, I'd pop over to the Princess Lucina Zoological Gardens and make friends with the octopus.

g.title: j2977150358
g.text: Poor little thing didn't get hurt, did it?

g.title: j406461222
g.text: Okay, I have to ask how that went.

g.title: j3360965097
g.text: I touched it. I’ve touched that thing with the very edge of my mind and I locked the memory away.

g.title: j968958939
g.text: ... and now I'm wishing I'd done that. Octopi are highly intelligent. We'd probably be writing poetry together by now. I wonder where that octopus is?

g.title: j1984251234
g.text: It was a dreadful three seconds for him.

g.title: j4272517078
g.text: I don’t even remember when it happened. She was giving one of her speeches on the tannoy, and I thought ‘I’ve never probed HER head before, I wonder what’s in there, probably all leather and needles’ and so I reached out and…

g.title: j2722576054
g.text: Someone probably ate it. That's what usually happens to zoo animals in quarantined cities, once supplies run out.

g.title: j3225071019
g.text: Poor little thing. I’d failed to allow for what touching MY mind would seem like to HIM, you see. Imagine a child lost in an infinite department store, screaming for its mother at the top of its lungs over and over. Everything was enormous and incomprehensible and had NOISES and SHAPES instead of SMELLS.

g.title: j1039496467
g.text: shitshitshit

g.title: j237227358
g.text: And whatever didn't get eaten will be riddled with Techrot by now.

g.title: j2537046689
g.text: I broke the link as fast as I could. He was a little dizzy for an hour or so, then he was fine. I doubt he even remembers what happened to him.

g.title: j954014286
g.text: I can’t talk about this yet. I’m sorry.

g.title: j262705388
g.text: ... which is how it was in the 'dream', isn't it? Only it isn't a dream at all. It happened. Or will happen. Or a version of it will. Something happens at that zoo.

g.title: j2602849498
g.text: And your side of it? What was it like being a rat?

g.title: j1654722322
g.text: It’s only a rat, come on.

g.title: j1609974498
g.text: +20 Chemistry

g.title: j10016929
g.text: I'm going to remember as much as I can.

g.title: j1991533408
g.text: I don’t know if you’ve ever had the kind of slump where all you want to do is lie in bed and breathe in and out and just exist without doing anything else, but it was a lot like that.

g.title: j3845632517
g.text: I wouldn’t let Lettie hear you say that. Not if you like your organs where they are.

g.title: j238837693
g.text: Boolean EleanorIndifference is now true.

g.title: j1483143494
g.text: Don't try to stop me.

g.title: j4195277366
g.text: Very basic. Simple needs met in simple ways.

g.title: j4221531654
g.text: Boolean EleanorRemembers is now true.

g.title: j4232514651
g.text: Childhood innocence has nothing on rat-consciousness.

g.title: j1058671663
g.text: Sounds kind of pleasant, the way you talk about it.

g.title: j3496619189
g.text: Are you jealous of a rat?

g.title: j699081338
g.text: Oh, it was. I’m sure being a rat has its bad side, like having to eat your dead brother so the predators won’t sniff him out, but that fleeting moment of simplicity was like a religious breakthrough, almost.

g.title: j3632018419
g.text: Sort of.

g.title: j1565403195
g.text: I guess being a rat is a lot like being a monk. Live off scraps, make your humble way in the world, never own a car or a house.

g.title: j1152459691
g.text: I just think there’s something heroic about being small and simple with very few needs.

g.title: j3305968710
g.text: Religious breakthrough?

g.title: j1675537944
g.text: I thought about being a nun for a long time, believe it or not.

g.title: j2469856504
g.text: Boolean EleanorNun1 is now true.

g.title: j148454612
g.text: You're going to have to tell me what that is, Eleanor.

g.title: j3752458676
g.text: A nun?

g.title: j3341037547
g.text: Right, yes. It seems they don't have them where you come from.

g.title: j2020941099
g.text: Right. Perhaps they don’t have them where you come from.

g.title: j3166385069
g.text: Like a devotee of Lua. Shaven head, white or black robes depending on the Aspect, very strict life. You’re expected to focus on holy things to the exclusion of all else. Prayer and meditation every day. Basic diet.

g.title: j3369956489
g.text: That sounds terrible.

g.title: j558299213
g.text: That sounds amazing.

g.title: j3114808282
g.text: That sounds challenging.

g.title: j1121290998
g.text: That sounds… like it’s not for me.

g.title: j2993760192
g.text: It does, on the face of it. About the only difference between the monastic life and prison is that you’re doing it on purpose.

g.title: j399430330
g.text: It sounds amazing to most young novices, too, until they actually get a taste of the monastic life. I think the quit rate is something like eighty per cent.

g.title: j2911882746
g.text: Oh, no. I mean, at first, yes, you’d need to wean yourself off all of the things that society has taught you to need. That phase is probably the hardest.

g.title: j3372175295
g.text: +10 Chemistry

g.title: j2511531545
g.text: Turns out it wasn't for me. I enjoy living in the world far too much.

g.title: j1503052925
g.text: But once you’re established, what’s the challenge going to be? Temptation? You’ll never SEE any. The idea is that you cut yourself off from everything that might distract you from the holy.

g.title: j3233364720
g.text: It wasn’t for me, either. It turns out I enjoy living in the world far too much.

g.title: j2053545781
g.text: But Sol… it’s like there’s some alternate version of me who’s sat on a mountaintop somewhere, incense clouds flowering around her, jet and moonstone beads ticking through her fingers, looking down on me with abject pity.

g.title: j3616895927
g.text: I know that’s just a fantasy. As much a fantasy as any of Arthur’s knights-in-armour pabulum.

g.title: j1523126673
g.text: We all fantasize about having our shit together one day.

g.title: j3108077781
g.text: I talk to an alternate version of myself all the time. We’ve had meals together. It’s not as crazy as you make it sound.

g.title: j3184082160
g.text: Thank you. For some reason that’s an incredibly comforting thing to hear.

g.title: j2695834142
g.text: Yes. I keep forgetting that what you’ve lived through amounts to pure bloody madness by any normal standard.

g.title: j2752343201
g.text: You know… I’ve never done this before, but I think I’ll try reaching out to her, just in case she exists. Yes. Maybe I can contact ‘Sister Eleanor’ telepathically.

g.title: j1883030150
g.text: What’s the worst that could happen?

g.title: j1911086634
g.text: +10 Chemistry

g.title: j413684356
g.text: I might get some words of guidance from my other self. Imagine that. Oh Lua, I’m quite excited now.

g.title: j2128066722
g.text: Boolean EleanorSister is now true.
